  <h2>Working smarter, not harder</h2>
  <p>It turns out when manually examine at a ballot, it tells you more than just which column to add a vote to. The <i>sequence</i> of votes is also important. Remember the old adage, "two steps forward, one step back"? We can use a similar intuition here.</p>

  <p>Professor Phillip Stark at the University of California, Berkeley applied fancy mathematics to this problem in order to audit ballots as efficiently as possible. He called this technique a "risk-limiting" audit. There are several different types of risk-limiting audits. While they differ in the ways that they go about selecting the ballots to be examined, each method provides a similar guarantee, backed by statistics, in the result of the election.</p>


  <p>The type of risk-limiting audit we will look at today is called a <i>ballot-polling audit</i>. The basic procedure, heavily simplified, looks as follows:
  </p>

  <ol>
    <li>Start a tally at 1</li>
    <li>Randomly select a ballot out of all the ballots cast.</li>
    <li>If the ballot contains a vote is for the supposed winner, multiply your total by some positive amount. Else, multiply by some fractional amount.</li>
    <li>Place the ballot back into the vote pool.</li>
    <li>Repeat steps 2 and 3 until you reach a threshold.</li>
  </ol>

